  "title": "Fixed point theorem and Picard’s theorem again",
  "body": " Fixed point theorem and Picard's theorem again    Note: 1 lecture (optional, does not require )  In this section we prove the fixed point theorem for contraction mappings. As an application we prove Picard's theorem, which we proved without metric spaces in . The proof presented here is similar, but it goes much more smoothly with metric spaces and the fixed point theorem.    Fixed point theorem    Let and be metric spaces. A map is a contraction contraction (or a contractive map) if it is a -Lipschitz map for some , i.e. if there exists a such that   Given a map , a point is called a fixed point fixed point if .     Contraction mapping principle contraction mapping principle or Banach fixed point theorem Banach fixed point theorem fixed point theorem    Named after the Polish mathematician Stefan Banach (1892–1945) who first stated the theorem in 1922. Let be a nonempty complete metric space and a contraction. Then has a unique fixed point.    The words complete and contraction are necessary. See .   Pick . Define a sequence by . Then Repeating times, we get . For , In particular, the sequence is Cauchy (why?). Since is complete, we let , and we claim that is our unique fixed point.  Fixed point? The function is a contraction, so it is Lipschitz continuous: Unique? Let and be fixed points. As , the inequality means that , and hence . The theorem is proved.   The proof is constructive. Not only do we know a unique fixed point exists, we know how to find it. Start with any point , then iterate , , , etc. to find better and better approximations. We can even find how far away from the fixed point we are. See the exercises. The idea of the proof is therefore useful in real-world applications.    Picard's theorem  We start with the metric space where we will apply the fixed point theorem: the space of , the space of continuous functions with the metric Convergence in this metric is convergence in uniform norm, or in other words, uniform convergence. Therefore, is a complete metric space, see .  Consider now the ordinary differential equation Given some , we desire a function such that and such that To avoid having to come up with many names, we often simply write for the equation and for the solution.  The simplest example is the equation , . The solution is the exponential . A somewhat more complicated example is , , whose solution is the Gaussian .  A subtle issue is how long the solution exists. Consider the equation , . Then is a solution. While is a reasonably nice function and in particular it exists for all and , the solution blows up at . For more examples related to Picard's theorem, see .  We will look for the solution in , which may feel strange at first as we are searching for a differentiable function. The explanation is that we consider the corresponding integral equation To solve this integral equation, we only need a continuous function, so in some sense our task should be easier—we have more candidate functions to try. This way of thinking is quite typical when solving differential equations.   Picard's theorem on existence and uniqueness  existence and uniqueness theorem  Picard's theorem   Let be closed and bounded intervals, let and be their interiors, and let . Suppose is continuous and Lipschitz in the second variable, that is, there exists an such that Then there exists an such that and a unique differentiable function such that      Without loss of generality, assume (exercise). As is compact and is continuous, is bounded. So find an such that for all . Pick such that and . Let Note . Let That is, is the set of continuous functions on with values in , in other words, exactly those functions where makes sense. It is left as an exercise to show that is a closed subset of (because is closed). The space is complete, and a closed subset of a complete metric space is a complete metric space with the subspace metric, see . So with the subspace metric is a complete metric space. We will write for this metric.  Define a mapping by It is an exercise to check that is well-defined, and that for , really is in . Let and . As is bounded by , we have So , and . In other words, . From now on, we consider as a mapping of to .  We claim is a contraction. First, for and , we have Therefore, We chose and so . Take supremum over of the left-hand side above to obtain , that is, is a contraction.  The fixed point theorem ( ) gives a unique such that . In other words, Clearly, . By the fundamental theorem of calculus ( ), is differentiable and its derivative is . Differentiable functions are continuous, so is the unique differentiable such that and .     For more exercises related to Picard's theorem see .    Let be a closed and bounded interval and . Show that is closed. Hint: is closed.      In the proof of Picard's theorem, show that if is continuous, then is continuous on as a function of . Use this to show that is well-defined and that .      Prove that in the proof of Picard's theorem, the statement Without loss of generality assume is justified. That is, prove that if we know the theorem with , the theorem is true as stated.      Let be defined by where , .    Show that is a contraction.    Find the fixed point and show directly that it is unique.        Let be defined by .    Show that is a contraction, and find the best (smallest) from the definition that works.    Find the fixed point and show directly that it is unique.            Find an example of a contraction of a non-complete metric space with no fixed point.    Find a 1-Lipschitz map of a complete metric space with no fixed point.        Consider , . Use the iteration scheme from the proof of the contraction mapping principle. Start with . Find a few iterates (at least up to ). Prove that the pointwise limit of is , that is, for every with for some , prove that .      Suppose is a contraction for . Suppose you use the iteration procedure with as in the proof of the fixed point theorem. Suppose is the fixed point of .    Show that for all .    Suppose for all , and . Find an such that starting at any given point , for all .        Let (you may recognize Newton's method for ).    Prove .    Prove that is a contraction.    Show that the fixed point theorem applies, find the unique such that , and show that . Note: In particular, the technique from the proof of the theorem can be used to approximate .        Suppose is a contraction, and is a metric space with the discrete metric, that is, whenever . Show that is constant, that is, there exists a such that for all .      Suppose is a nonempty complete metric space, is a mapping, and denote by the th iterate of . Suppose for every there exists a such that for all , where . Prove that has a unique fixed point in .     "
