  "body": " Differentiation under the integral   Note: less than 1 lecture  Let be a function of two variables, and define If is continuous on the compact rectangle , then says that is continuous on .  Suppose is differentiable in . When can we differentiate under the integral ? That is, when is it true that is differentiable and its derivative is Differentiation is a limit and therefore we are really asking when the two limiting operations of integration and differentiation commute. It is not always possible to commute them and some extra hypothesis is necessary. The first question we would face is the integrability of , but the formula above can fail even if is integrable as a function of for every fixed .  We prove a simple, but perhaps the most useful, version of this kind of result.   Leibniz integral rule Leibniz integral rule   Suppose is a continuous function, such that exists for all and is continuous. Define by Then is continuously differentiable and     The hypotheses on and can be weakened, see e.g. , but not dropped outright. The main point in the proof requires that exists and is continuous for all up to the endpoints, but we only need a small interval in the direction. In applications, we often make a small interval around the point where we need to differentiate.   Fix and let be given. As is continuous on it is uniformly continuous. In particular, there exists such that whenever with and all , we have   Suppose is such that and . Fix for a moment and apply the mean value theorem to find a between and such that As , The argument worked for every (different may have been used). Thus, as a function of  We defined uniform convergence for sequences although the idea is the same. You may replace with a sequence of nonzero numbers converging to such that and let .  Consider the difference quotient of , Uniform convergence implies the limit can be taken underneath the integral. So Then is continuous on by mentioned above.     Let Then       Consider The function under the integral extends to be continuous on , and hence the integral exists, see . Trouble is finding it. We introduce a parameter and define a function: The function also extends to a continuous function of and for (also part of the exercise). See .   The graph on .  Surface plot of a function in the first quadrant on the xy-plane. The function is zero on both the x and the y axes, however it rises very steeply from the y-axis.   Hence, is a continuous function on and . For every , the derivative of the integrand, , is continuous on . Therefore, for , we may differentiate under the integral sign, We need to figure out given that and . Elementary calculus says that . Thus,        Prove the two statements that were asserted in :    Prove extends to a continuous function of . That is, there exists a continuous function on that equals on .    Prove extends to a continuous function on .        Suppose is continuous and is continuously differentiable and compactly supported. That is, there exists some , such that whenever . Define Show that is differentiable.      Suppose is infinitely differentiable (derivatives of all orders exist) and . Show that there exists an infinitely differentiable function such that . Show also that if , then . Hint: Write and then rewrite the integral to go from to .      Compute . Derive the formula for not using integration by parts, but by differentiation underneath the integral.      Let be open and suppose is a continuous function defined on . Suppose exist and are continuous on . Prove that defined by is continuously differentiable.     The graph on .  Surface plot of a function on the unit square. On the axes the function is zero and is otherwise positive, except at the origin, where there seems to be a discontinuity and it appears that as we move from the inside of the square towards the origin we would attain a positive value rather than zero.     Work out the following counterexample: Let See .    Prove that for every fixed , the function is Riemann integrable on , and Therefore, exists and is the continuous function     Prove exists at all and and compute it.    Show that for all  exists, but         Work out the following counterexample: Let     Prove is continuous on all of . Therefore the following function is well-defined for every :     Prove exists for all , but is not continuous at .    Show that does not exist even if we take improper integrals, that is, that the limit does not exist.    Note: Feel free to use what you know about sine and cosine from calculus.      Strengthen the Leibniz integral rule in the following way. Suppose is a bounded continuous function, such that exists for all and is continuous and bounded. Define by Then is continuously differentiable and Hint: See also and .      Suppose is continuously differentiable, is continuous, exists and is continuous at all points. Show that is continuously differentiable, and that it is the solution of the partial differential equation , with the initial condition for all .     "
