  "title": "Iterated integrals and the Fubini theorem",
  "body": " Iterated integrals and the Fubini theorem   Note: 1–2 lectures  The Riemann integral in several variables is hard to compute via the definition. For the one-dimensional Riemann integral, we have the fundamental theorem of calculus (see ), which allows computing many integrals without having to appeal to the definition of the integral. We will rewrite a Riemann integral in several variables into several one-dimensional Riemann integrals by iterating. However, if is a Riemann integrable function, it is not immediately clear if the three expressions are equal, or if the last two are even well-defined.    Define Then is Riemann integrable on and . Moreover, . However, does not exist, so strictly speaking, does not make sense. See .   Left: with the line marked dotted and marked as a gray solid line for a generic . Center: Similar picture but marked for some . Right: The three different rectangles in the partition used to integrate in different grays.  Three diagrams of squares. On the left a white square with a horizontal gray line in the upper part of the square and a vertical dotted line running through the middle. In the middle diagram, there is the same dotted line, but the gray line now is also vertical in the left part of the square. The right diagram has the same dotted line with a dashed vertical line very near on each side. The region to the left of the first dotted line is shaded dark, the region to the right of the second dotted line is shaded in medium gray, and the thin region around the dotted line is shaded in the lightest color.   Proof: We start with integrability of . Consider the partition of where the partition in the direction is and in the direction . The corresponding subrectangles are We have , , , and . Therefore, and The upper and lower sums are arbitrarily close and the lower sum is always zero, so the function is integrable and .  For every fixed , the function that takes to is zero except perhaps at a single point . Such a function is integrable and . Therefore, . However, if , the function that takes to is the nonintegrable function that is 1 on the rationals and 0 on the irrationals. See .    We solve this problem of undefined inside integrals by using the upper and lower integrals, which are always defined for any bounded function.  Split the coordinates of into two parts: Write the coordinates on as where and . For a function , write when is fixed and we want a function of . Write when is fixed and we want a function of .   Fubini version A  Fubini's theorem    Named after the Italian mathematician Guido Fubini (1879–1943). Let be a closed rectangle and be integrable. The functions and defined by are integrable on and     In other words, If is integrable for all , for example when is continuous, we obtain the more familiar    A partition of can be written as , where and are partitions of and respectively. Let be the subrectangles of and be the subrectangles of . The subrectangles of are where and .  Let Notice that and hence Define For , we have , and therefore, The inequality holds for all , and so We obtain   Similarly, , and the proof of this inequality is left as an exercise. Putting the two inequalities together with the fact that for all , Since is integrable, it must be that is integrable as and we can make the right-hand side arbitrarily small. As for any partition we have , we have .  Likewise, and hence As is integrable, so is . Moreover, implies .   We can also do the iterated integration in the opposite order. The proof of this version is almost identical to version A (or follows quickly from version A). We leave it as an exercise.   Fubini version B  Fubini's theorem   Let be a closed rectangle and be integrable. The functions and defined by are integrable on and     That is,   Next suppose and are integrable. For example, suppose is continuous. By putting the two versions together we obtain the familiar   Often the Fubini theorem is stated in two dimensions for a continuous function on a rectangle . Then the Fubini theorem states that The Fubini theorem is commonly thought of as the theorem that allows us to swap the order of iterated integrals, although there are many variations on Fubini, and we have seen but two of them.  Repeatedly applying the Fubini theorem gives the following corollary: Let be a closed rectangle and let be continuous. Then   We may switch the order of integration to any order we please. We may relax the continuity requirement by making sure that all the intermediate functions are integrable, or by using upper or lower integrals appropriately.     Compute in a simple way.      Prove the assertion from the proof of .       (Easy) Prove .      Let and be an integrable function on such that for every fixed , the function that takes to is zero except at finitely many points. Show       Let and for continuous functions and . Prove       Compute (using calculus) You will need to interpret the integrals as improper, that is, the limit of as .      Suppose where is Riemann integrable. Show that is Riemann integrable for every and       Define by     Show exists, but does not.    Compute and .    Show is not Riemann integrable on (use Fubini).        Define by     Show is Riemann integrable on .    Find and for all , and show they are unequal for all .    Show exists, but does not.    Note: By Fubini, and exist and equal .     "
