  "number": "11.1",
  "title": "Complex numbers",
  "body": " Complex numbers    Note: half a lecture    The complex plane  In this chapter, we consider approximation of functions, or in other words, functions as limits of sequences and series. We will extend some results we already saw to a somewhat more general setting, and we will look at some completely new results. In particular, we consider complex-valued functions. We gave complex numbers as examples before, but let us start from scratch and properly define the complex number field.  A complex number is just a pair on which we define multiplication (see below). We call the set the complex numbers complex number and denote it by . We identify with . The -axis is then called the real axis real axis and the -axis is called the imaginary axis imaginary axis . As is just the plane, we also call the set the complex plane complex plane .  Define: Under the identification above, we have and . These two operations make the plane into a field (exercise). We write a complex number as , where we define Note that engineers use instead of .  Notice that . That is, is a solution to the polynomial equation From now on, we will not use the notation and use only . See .   The points , , , , and in the complex plane.  Diagram of a number in the complex plane. The number 1 is marked on the horizontal axis to the right of the origin, and the number i is marked on the vertical axis above the origin. The number x is marked on the horizontal axis and a number i y is marked on the vertical axis. The combination x plus i y is marked at the point (x,y).   We generally use for real values and for complex values, although that is not a hard and fast rule. In particular, is often used as a third real variable in .    Suppose . We call the real part real part of , and we call the imaginary part imaginary part of . We write Define complex conjugate complex conjugate as and define modulus modulus as     Modulus is the complex analogue of the absolute value and has similar properties. For example, (exercise). The complex conjugate is a reflection of the plane across the real axis. The real numbers are precisely those numbers for which the imaginary part . In particular, they are precisely those numbers which satisfy the equation   As is really , we let the metric on be the standard euclidean metric on . In particular, So the topology on is the same exact topology as the standard topology on with the euclidean metric, and is equal to the euclidean norm on . Importantly, since is a complete metric space, then so is . As is the euclidean norm on , we have the triangle inequality triangle inequality complex numbers of both flavors:   The complex conjugate and the modulus are even more intimately related:     There is no natural ordering on the complex numbers. In particular, no ordering that makes the complex numbers into an ordered field. Ordering is one of the things we lose when we go from real to complex numbers.      Complex numbers and limits  Algebraic operations with complex numbers are continuous because convergence in is the same as convergence for each component, and we already know that the real algebraic operations are continuous. For example, write and , and suppose that and . Let us show First, The topology on is the same as on , and so , , , and . Hence, As ,   Similarly, the modulus and the complex conjugate are continuous functions. We leave the remainder of the proof of the following proposition as an exercise.    Suppose , are sequences of complex numbers converging to and respectively. Then     .     .    Assuming for all and , .     .     .      As we have seen above, convergence in is the same as convergence in . In particular, a sequence in converges if and only if the real and imaginary parts converge. Therefore, feel free to apply everything you have learned about convergence in , as well as applying results about real numbers to the real and imaginary parts.  We also need convergence of complex series. Let be a sequence of complex numbers. The series  converges converges complex series if the sequence of partial sums converges, that is, if A series converges absolutely converges absolutely complex series if converges.  We say a series is Cauchy Cauchy complex series if the sequence of partial sums is Cauchy. The following two propositions have essentially the same proofs as their analogues for real series and we leave them as exercises.    The complex series is Cauchy if for every , there exists an such that for every and every , we have       If a complex series converges absolutely, then it converges.    The series is a real series. All the convergence tests (ratio test, root test, etc.) that talk about absolute convergence work with the numbers , that is, they are really talking about convergence of series of nonnegative real numbers. You can directly apply these tests without needing to reprove anything for complex series.    Complex-valued functions  When we deal with complex-valued functions , we often write for real-valued functions and .  Suppose we wish to integrate . We write for real-valued and . We say that is Riemann integrable Riemann integrable complex-valued function if and are Riemann integrable, and in this case we define We make the same definition for every other type of integral (improper, multivariable, etc.).  Similarly when we differentiate, write as . Thinking of as , we say that is differentiable if and are differentiable. For a function valued in , the derivative is represented by a vector in . Now a vector in is a complex number. In other words, we write the derivative derivative complex-valued function as The linear operator representing the derivative is the multiplication by the complex number , so nothing is lost in this identification.      Check that is a field.      Prove that for , we have .      Finish the proof of .      Prove .      Prove .      Given define the matrix . Prove:    The action of this matrix on a vector is the same as multiplying .    Multiplying two such matrices is the same multiplying the underlying complex numbers and then finding the corresponding matrix for the product. In other words, the field can be identified with a subset of the 2-by-2 matrices.    The matrix has eigenvalues and . Recall that is an eigenvalue of a matrix if (a complex matrix in our case) is not invertible, that is, if it has linearly dependent rows: one row is a (complex) multiple of the other.        Prove the Bolzano–Weierstrass theorem for complex sequences. Suppose is a bounded sequence of complex numbers. That is, there exists an such that for all . Prove that there exists a subsequence that converges to some .          Prove that there is no simple mean value theorem for complex-valued functions: Find a differentiable function such that , but for all .    However, there is a weaker form of the mean value theorem as there is for vector-valued functions. Prove: If is continuous and differentiable in , and for some , for all , then .        Prove that there is no simple mean value theorem for integrals for complex-valued functions: Find a continuous function such that but for all .     "
